I hate Land Rovers...  Dont get me wrong, they are well built, study cars, but thats what they are, Cars.. Land Rover used to be fantastic, the original Defender was one of the best 4x4 trucks out there, it was rugged, tough, mechanically simplistic, had a center differential so that it could be in permanent 4x4.  Now look at this Range Rover, in assuming that Land Rover knew what top gear were doing in this video (which im sure they did) This car is totally unsuited for this terrain, The wheels are like 20 Inch wheels, which is way too big to get any real off road tire (Eg: BF Goodrich All Terrain T/A KO2's, Mickey Thompson Deegan 38.. ect), there is hardly any room for the suspension to travel anywhere. Furthermore, This car is way too low, there is bugger all clearance from anything. SPEAKING OF WHICH, look at the angles of Attack, exit and ramp over, this car is way too long, with too much body in the front and rear of the car.. this would be useless in any kind of serious offroad work  Not to mention the cost of a Land Rover is Prohibitive at best!  The Great age of the offroad 4x4 trucks died in the '90s, Land Rover just hasnt seen it yet

British "TV" audiences really have NO idea about continuity what so ever. This was more than likely filmed over 4 days, consisting of 1 day of ground, wheel & back shots, 1 day of Ariel Shots, 1 day of Effects Shots, Wide Angles & Crane movements, & then 1 day to film all May's "Scripted" bullshit.   It's then edited frenetically by chopping all the parts together with NO sense of pace, geography, scale, narrative or realism with silly epic music, typical outdated cringe-worthy British humour, Slow-Mo, annoying sound effects, & CGI map overlays to compensate & glue it all together.   I'm so glad I told the TV-License people where to stick it. The internet is hard to get to grips with at first..  having no strobe edits & epic music!! But now when I see clips like these, I see past all the bullshit, all the advertisements, product placements, scripted gags, premeditated story boards etc to a very brainwashed stylised form of trend-reliant entertainment at its' worst. As Shakespeare would say...  "Full of Sound & Fury; Signifying Nothing".   I wouldn't be suprised if the Americans won, & they simply filmed the flare scene 2 days later & edited together. What ever this audience sees - they believe.

+FullSpectrum Survivalist   You do know that the 6x6 TerraMax in this video has full independent suspension, right? Independent suspension, properly equip will be better than a solid axle for off road.  The rock crawlers/jeep guys can have more flex/travel with their solid axles but why do you need all 4 wheels to be touching the ground if you have diff locks? While there is many more capable vehicles than the Landrover, the Landrover is a very luxurious vehicle that can go pretty much anywhere.  Even more impressive is they used the stock tires.

Rick V That's a 6X6 vehicle. In a 4 wheel drive independent suspension will get your ride turned over, so no a Land Rover will not go where a solid axle can go, and a Jeep will go better, and do it cheaper. They use stock tires because they don't really have much of a choice due to design of the Land Rover not being capable of being upgraded to large tires, so how is that impressive? Have you ever saw a LandÂ  Rover turn over trying to ascend a steep grade?, well I have, and independent suspension is why. I can tell you he wished he had a live axle that day. Off Roading isn't about luxury.

There is also many serious military 4x4 vehicles with independent suspension.  With independent suspension, you get way more ground clearance.  95% of the vehicles on the road today with independent suspension suck offroad because they are not designed for offroad but that does not mean that independent suspension vehicles are not capable of going off road.  Jeeps have solid axles because of just that, they are cheaper to offroad with. But you still have the differential hanging down low. I've seen many jeeps turn over. There is this magic bar call the sway bar that reduced roll over. Most jeeps remove there's so they can have all 4 wheels touching the ground (more suspension flex) which if they are serious jeeps, they already have lockers, with lockers, you only need two wheels touching the ground as all 4 wheels will have the same power going to them and the 2 that are hanging down will not even have weight on them so they are doing very little anyways.  Landrover,  like Jeep has always had very offroad capable vehicles,  then they started getting more into the luxury side and while 95% of the people that own a range rover will likely never see a gravel road, they are still very capable vehicles.  Just like the Grand Cherokee,  many will argue that the older jeeps were way better than the new wk2 but they can still go many places offroad.  They make lift kits and I believe most will fit 17 inch tires which will have a huge selection of off road tires. There is many videos with a stock jeep grand Cherokee teetering on 2 wheels and still keeps going.  I'm pretty sure that there is many other tire choices in the size the Landrover uses. And if we are going to compare modified jeeps, a person could always put smaller brakes on the land Rover and fit smaller wheels/bigger tires. Rally cars do that all the time to fit 14 or 15 inch tires.  Yes a modified jeep will go more places for cheaper but I bet stock for stock, the Landrover will go the same places as any stock jeep will. Once you start modifing a Landrover or any independent suspension vehicle,  the independent suspension vehicle will cost way more but will be better offroad. Why do you think all the big ATVs have independent suspension? It's that little bit of extra ground clearance that helps it go more places. Offroading is not about luxury, you are right there but the Landrover makes high end luxury vehicles that are still very capable offroad.

Rick V "And if we are going to compare modified jeeps, a person could always put smaller brakes on the land Rover and fit smaller wheels/bigger tires."  No you can't, there is a physical barrier, the brakes are not the problem, the design of the vehicle is, research it.

JP Onefourseven Probably meant stock...

Jeb Watson A new 70 series Toyota Landcruiser comes stock with bullbar, winch and front and rear diff locks, as well as a turbo diesel V8. Wranglers can also come stock with diff locks. Plus, both these vehicles have solid front and rear axles. A stock GU Nissan Patrol and a new Land Rover Defender are also for better stock 4x4s, just to name a few.Â  I'm not saying the RR is a bad car, it does have good gearing and the traction control helps it a lot, but it really doesn't compare to more serious 4x4s.Â  Had they said it was the best off road luxury SUV in the world, I might beleive that.

While I can appreciate the lockers, the RR takes a different approach using its brakes to do the exact same thing as lockers would only better. It has a supercharged V8 so no shortage of power or torque. The only thing holding the RR back is its low profile tires and large body. So I have to respectfully disagree with you.

Jeb Watson The traction control works fine for getting over obstacles. The problem is not the lack of lockers, it is the lack of travel. The RR is just too happy to lift a wheel or 2. While it has no trouble putting the power to the wheels that are still on the ground, you will always be better off with power going to 4 wheels on the ground rather than just 2 or 3. The RR is great for what it is, I would even say it is one of the best new 4x4s you can buy. But it is not even in the same league as a new 70 Series 'Cruiser.

I will admit that the lack of articulation does and has always bothered me. I would much rather have beefier tires and a longer traveling suspension (though not a solid axle since that kind of defeats all of the technology that the new RR operates on). Jeb Watson you clearly do not understand how lockers and open differentials work. An open diff sends torque to one wheel once the spider gears start spinning. Brakes cannot lock the diff for you at all, unless you had a torsen style differential. Lockers are SUBSTANTIALLY better, which is why they are regular gear on actual off road (stock or modified) vehicles. If it were close then they would just use the brakes and no one would care, but RR fans aren't educated well enough on 4x4 dynamics to care; nor would they ever put their rig in a situation where they could even tell.  A locker has no differentiation of speed between the wheels. Torque is sent to both wheels, and when one wheel has less traction it still won't spin until the other wheel(s) locked to it lose traction as well. That means, for the Rubicon wrangler (zr2 colorado, ram power wagon, and every other 4x4 system with a fully locked driveline), that you must overwhelm the traction of all 4 tires in order to lose grip. It also means that all 4 wheels simultaneously digg for traction. With an open differential and the brakes slowing/stopping the spinning wheel you have a few things going on. First, the open diff is only sending torque to one wheel and the brake is adding resistance to the other wheel with lower traction to force torque to the one with greater traction (but now higher resistance thanks to the brakes). Second, one wheel has its BRAKE engaged, which means it is resisting movement thus momentum. When wheeling hard one could easily feel this happening, especially on the front axle where the vehicle wants to turn towards the wheel being slowed/stopped by the traction control.   So, do you think a rear limited slip (which acts like a locker but with far less dynamic torque transfer ability (only can transmit as much as the clutch or helical gears can lock up) with an open front differential  (can only send equal torque to both wheels that cannot exceed the resistance of the lesser wheel before the spider gears move and transfer torque to ONLY the wheel with the least resistance) can compete with a true locked 4x4. The range rovers 4wd system under severe conditions acts more like a 2 and 1/2 to 3 wheel drive depending on the torque demands on the rear clutch pack.

It may be "fake", but it's fake in that they chose a route that would result in a close race, and most likely tested it several times before turning on the cameras. This makes sense when your goal is to create a watchable television program.  As long as a win for the other competitor would be equally interesting television, which is usually the case, they have no incentive to outright falsify the results.  When they do want one side to win (every "car vs X" competition) they choose the right conditions to give the opponent as big a handicap as possible without making it obvious, but they don't tell the opponent to throw the race on purpose.  That said, I was expecting the truck to be on his tail for a while with a "Duel" reference thrown in. Missed chance there, kayfabe writers!
